{
  "text": "While we are encouraged by these findings, this work falls short of establishing the reliability and validity of the TICS-M in MS. The psychometric standards necessary for validation are well known [CITATION_1] , and this study did not examine test-retest reliability, sensitivity compared to conventional testing, or convergent validity. We acknowledge that the TICS-M emphasizes verbal memory and language, domains that are more relevant for mild cognitive impairment and Alzheimer Disease, and, are a better match for a telephonebased assessment. Furthermore, assessment of visualrelated cognitive deficits cannot be assessed with the TICS-M and processing speed is not measured. However, the TICS-M has been utilized successfully in randomized controlled trials and large-scale population studies [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] and we are presently pursuing similar approaches for the MS community using the Brief International Cognitive Assessment for MS [CITATION_4] as a base for this assessment. Pilot work [CITATION_5] suggests that a telemedicine approach to the symbol digit modalities test is feasible, although the optimal format and test form is yet to be determined. Other pilot work suggests that remotely-delivered cognitive remediation is feasible for individuals with MS [CITATION_6] . Further, our study participants did not refuse testing for depression which must be measured at the time of any cognitive assessment in MS. This finding also supports the feasibility of remote cognitive testing.",
  "correct_citation": {
